# Git Commit Overlay (`c` key in Git Panel)

## Overview
Add a `c` keybinding to the Git Actions panel that stages all changes, generates a commit message via `claude -p` one-shot, and presents an editable overlay for review before committing. Optionally push after commit.

## Flow
1. User presses `c` in Git panel (actions focused)
2. Azureal runs `git add -A` + `git diff --staged` in the worktree
3. If no staged changes → show result message "Nothing to commit" and abort
4. Show loading indicator "Generating commit message…"
5. Spawn `claude -p "Write a conventional commit message for this diff (type: short desc on first line, optional body with bullets). Only output the message, nothing else.\n\n<diff>"` as a background thread (NOT a full session — just `std::process::Command` with stdout capture)
6. When Claude returns, populate the commit overlay with the generated message
7. User can edit the message, then:
   - `Enter` → `git commit -m "<message>"` → show result, refresh changed files
   - `p` → `git commit -m "<message>"` + `git push` → show result
   - `Esc` → cancel, close overlay
8. After commit/push, close overlay and show result message in the Git panel

## Files to Modify

### 1. `src/tui/keybindings.rs`
- Add `Action::GitCommit` variant to the `Action` enum
- Add `c` keybinding to `GIT_ACTIONS` array (guard: actions_focused only, same as other git ops)
- Add `GitCommit` to `git_actions_labels()` so it shows in the action list
- Update `git_actions_footer()` if needed
- ACTION_COUNT in input_git_actions.rs bumps from 6 → 7

### 2. `src/app/types.rs`
- Add `commit_overlay` field to `GitActionsPanel`: `Option<GitCommitOverlay>`
- New struct `GitCommitOverlay`:
  - `message: String` — the editable commit message
  - `cursor: usize` — cursor position (char index) in the message
  - `generating: bool` — true while Claude is still generating
  - `scroll: usize` — scroll offset for long messages

### 3. `src/git/core.rs`
- Add `Git::stage_all(worktree_path)` → runs `git add -A`
- Add `Git::get_staged_diff(worktree_path)` → runs `git diff --staged` and returns the text
- Add `Git::commit(worktree_path, message)` → runs `git commit -m "<message>"`

### 4. `src/tui/input_git_actions.rs`
- Bump `ACTION_COUNT` from 6 → 7
- Add `Action::GitCommit` match arm in the action dispatcher → calls `exec_commit_start(app)`
- Add index 6 to the `Confirm` match for Enter-on-action-row
- Add `handle_commit_overlay()` function — intercepts all input when `commit_overlay.is_some()`:
  - `Enter` → exec commit (and close overlay)
  - `p` → exec commit + push (and close overlay)
  - `Esc` → cancel (close overlay)
  - `Backspace` / typing → edit the message text
  - `↑/↓` → scroll through multi-line message
  - Arrow keys → move cursor within text
- `exec_commit_start(app)` function:
  - Calls `Git::stage_all()` + `Git::get_staged_diff()`
  - If diff empty → set result_message "Nothing to commit", return
  - Set `commit_overlay = Some(GitCommitOverlay { message: "", cursor: 0, generating: true, scroll: 0 })`
  - Spawn background thread: run `claude -p` with diff, send result back via `mpsc::channel`
  - Store the receiver on the overlay (or on App) for polling

### 5. `src/tui/draw_git_actions.rs`
- Add commit overlay rendering (similar to auto-rebase scope dialog but larger):
  - Centered dialog on top of the Git panel (70% of panel width, 50% height)
  - Title: " Commit " in orange
  - Body: the editable message text with cursor
  - If `generating` is true, show "Generating…" spinner/text
  - Bottom hint line: `Enter:commit  p:commit+push  Esc:cancel`

### 6. `src/tui/event_loop.rs` or `src/tui/event_loop/claude_events.rs`
- Poll the commit message receiver in the event loop (similar to how claude_receivers are polled)
- When message arrives: set `commit_overlay.message = result`, `generating = false`, cursor to end

## Design Decisions

**Why `std::process::Command` not a Claude session:**
- One-shot `claude -p` is fire-and-forget, no session file, no JSONL, no streaming needed
- ~3 second turnaround vs 10+ for full session setup
- Zero API session overhead
- The diff provides all context needed

**Why background thread:**
- Claude one-shot takes ~3 seconds — can't block the event loop
- Spawn thread, send result back via mpsc, poll in event loop
- Show "Generating…" state while waiting

**Why editable:**
- User can tweak the message before committing
- Basic text editing: type, backspace, arrow keys
- Multi-line support with scroll for long messages

**Overlay stacking:**
- Commit overlay renders on top of the Git panel (same pattern as auto-rebase scope picker)
- When commit overlay is open, it intercepts all input (same pattern as autorebase_scope)
